1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 h6 5. Bh4 c5 6. d5 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. e3
e5 9. f3 Bf5 $1 {I like this move very much! Its logic is very simple: White
would like to play Bd3 without allowing the move e4 from Black - hence he
played f3. But Black now develops his bishop on that diagonal, to d3. He is
ready to exchange the bishops, after which the c4 pawn will become a potential
weakness.} 10. Qb3 (10. e4 Bc8 {The bishop returns back. But look at the
damage it has caused - the f1 bishop is totally passive now!}) 10... b6 11. h3
{Somehow I am not able to explain this move made by Timman. Why did he have to
play h3? If he wanted to play g4, he could already have done it.} Nbd7 12. g4
Bh7 {Black is well developed.} 13. Ne2 g5 {As is usual in this variation, this
move is nothing new.} 14. Bf2 h5 (14... e4 {Would be strongly met with...} 15.
f4 $1) 15. h4 $5 (15. e4 {Would have been an interesting move. Now White's
idea is to play Be3 and attack the g5 pawn.} h4 16. Be3 Ng8 $1 {Black now
plans Nf8-g6; the position is quite equal.}) 15... e4 $6 (15... hxg4 $1 16.
hxg5 gxf3 17. Ng3 Ng4 18. Bd3 Qxg5 19. Bxh7 Nxe3 $17 {Would have demolished
White's position!}) 16. hxg5 exf3 17. gxf6 fxe2 (17... hxg4 18. Nf4 Qxf6 {
Gives Black sufficient compensation.}) 18. Bxe2 Qxf6 19. Rxh5 Bg6 20. Bh4 (20.
Rxh8+ Qxh8 {Gives Black a good position.}) 20... Qg7 21. Kd2 Bxh5 22. gxh5 Qg2
{The main point in this position is that the 'h' pawn, with the two bishops,
gives Black enough compensation. But Black will sacrifice his exchange back
and then positionally White will be worse. This is the problem with White's
position in general: even if he wins material, he is usually left with a poor
pawn structure.} 23. Rf1 Rxh5 $1 24. Rf2 Qh3 25. Bxh5 Qxh4 26. Rf5 (26. Bxf7+
Ke7 $19) 26... Ne5 {Black has a strong knight against White's not so strong
bishop. In the game, Roman showed good technique and was able to overwhelm
Timman in the endgame.} 27. Be2 O-O-O 28. a4 Rg8 29. Qb5 Qe7 30. Rh5 Qd7 31.
Qa6+ Qb7 32. Qb5 a6 33. Qb1 Qc7 34. Rh6 Kb7 35. Qf5 Rg6 36. Rh7 Qe7 37. Qh3 Rg8
38. Kc2 Kc7 39. Bh5 Qf6 40. Kb3 Rh8 41. Rxh8 Qxh8 42. Qf5 Qg7 43. Qe4 Qg5 44.
Bd1 Qg6 45. Qc2 Qxc2+ 46. Bxc2 Ng4 47. e4 Ne5 48. Bd1 a5 49. Be2 Kd7 50. Kc2
Ke7 51. Kd2 Kf6 52. Ke3 Kg5 53. Bd1 Nxc4+ 54. Kf3 f5 55. exf5 Kxf5 56. Ke2 Kf4
57. Bb3 Nb2 58. Kd2 c4 59. Ba2 Ke4 60. Kc2 Nxa4 61. Bxc4 Nc5 62. Kb2 Nd3+ 63.
Ka3 Ne5 64. Ba2 b5 {Dzindzichashivili's idea of Bf5 against f3 is worth
keeping in mind. It puts White in a quandary whether to play e4 or Bd3, or
play like Timman did - which is very risky!} 0-1

