1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 c5 5. d5 d6 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3
e5 9. Qc2 {This is quite an interesting move. It stops 9...Bf5 which Black
would play in case of 9.f3. So we have to come up with a new plan.} Qe7 10. Nf3
(10. Bd3 $6 g5 $1 11. Bg3 e4 12. Be2 {White has just lost a lot of time.})
10... Kd8 $1 {Nigel Short shows that Karpov's idea of parking the king on c7
can be executed even before developing the queen side pieces.} 11. Nd2 Kc7 {As
always, the king is extremely safe here.} 12. Bd3 g5 13. Bg3 Nh5 {Not that we
would like to take the bishop on g3. We may or we may not: we just keep a
watch on it. Maybe some day we could also plan Ng7 and f5.} 14. O-O-O $5 {I
have a belief that Black is simply better in this position. This is due to the
fact that he had given up his bishop on c3. So we can say that the
dark-squared bishop is White's prized possession for the queen side weaknesses
that he has incurred. But that bishop is causing not even a little bit of harm
to Black. Hence the pawn weaknesses remain, which will soon be counted in the
endgame.} Nd7 15. Rde1 {Angling to break open the position with f4.} Ndf6 16.
f3 {White would like to preserve his prized possession - the dark-squared
bishop. But Black is having none of it: he takes the bishop off the board.} (
16. f4 {Is not really possible now as Black plays...} Nxg3 $1 {This is what I
meant when I said that the knight on h5 keeps an eye on the bishop on g3 and
takes it at the most appropriate moment.} 17. hxg3 Bg4 $15 {White is saddled
with pawn weaknesses and Black has his development in order. In short,
advantage Black.}) 16... Nxg3 17. hxg3 Bd7 {Completing his development. The
idea now is to play on the king side with the pawns on the 'h' and 'g' files.}
18. Rh2 h5 19. Kb1 g4 {White doesn't have any active plans and Black is
clearly pushing.} 20. Ka1 Rhg8 21. f4 {White had to make this move to protect
his g3 weakness.} h4 $1 {A highly unexpected move! The point is that the 'e'
pawn is pinned, as the rook on e1 is unprotected and the g3 pawn will support
the rook on h4; so after Rh4 ef4, White will be in a situation as to how to
recapture f4!} 22. Rxh4 exf4 23. gxf4 Nxd5 $1 {Black wins back the pawn and
now exposes White's structure even further.} 24. Rhh1 Nb6 {The c4 pawn is now
easier to attack with Be6.} 25. e4 Rh8 26. Rhf1 Rh2 27. Nb3 Rah8 28. e5 Bc6 29.
Be4 Nxc4 30. Bxc6 bxc6 31. exd6+ Qxd6 32. Qf5 Qd5 33. Re7+ Kb6 34. Qxd5 cxd5
35. Rxf7 Rh1 36. Rb1 Rxb1+ 37. Kxb1 Rh1+ 38. Kc2 Rh2 39. Rf6+ Kc7 40. Nxc5
Rxg2+ 41. Kd1 g3 42. Rg6 Rd2+ 43. Ke1 g2 44. Ne6+ Kd7 45. Nd4 Rxa2 46. Ne2 a5
47. Rxg2 a4 48. Rg7+ Kd6 49. Rg6+ Ke7 50. Ra6 a3 51. Nd4 Rb2 52. Nc6+ Kf7 53.
Nb4 d4 54. Rc6 Nd2 55. Ra6 Nb1 56. Nd5 Nxc3 57. Ra7+ Ke6 58. Nc7+ Kd6 59. Ne8+
Kc6 60. Ra6+ Kb7 {To summarize this game, the idea of Kd8-c7 at the earliest
possible moment looks quite attractive to me. To keep pressure on g3 bishop
with knight on h5 is very irritating for White and then to exchange it at the
right moment and push the king side pawns is strategically very difficult to
counter. All in all, I would say it's quite a joy to see 4.Bg5 on the board!}
0-1

