{This was played six years ago when I was a relatively inexperienced player. I
was facing a strong Indian IM, C.S. Gokhale, who is known to play the
Leningrad system against the Nimzo. I looked at the Jussupow-Short game and
was thoroughly impressed by Short's play, and decided to follow him. And I
must say the game went off excellently for me!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
4. Bg5 c5 5. d5 h6 6. Bh4 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. e3 e5 9. Qc2 Qe7 10. Nf3 Kd8 $1 {
I decided to follow the footsteps of Nigel Short!} 11. Nd2 Kc7 12. Bd3 g5 13.
Bg3 Nh5 {Keeping an eye on the dark-squared bishop.} 14. O-O {Unlike Yusupov,
Gokhale decides to castle short, but I think this is worse as he will come
under attack now from my advanced king side pawns.} Nd7 15. Rae1 {Planning for
f4, which really is not possible as Black will just take on g3.} Rg8 $1 {
Putting pressure on the 'g' file so that f4 is not possible.} (15... Ndf6 {Was
another way to play; f4 really is not on the cards.} 16. f4 Nxg3 17. hxg3 Bg4
$15) 16. a4 Ndf6 (16... a5 {Could it have been more prudent to follow Karpov's
strategy and to fix this pawn here? Well, maybe it would have been, for
example...} 17. Rb1 Ndf6 18. Qb3 Ra6 19. Bf5 Kb8 20. Bxc8 Rxc8 {I don't see
much inherently wrong with Black's position. A word of caution: computers can
hardly understand this position as they are unable to come up with a plan. You
can play for a few moves and see how the computer's evaluation loses faith in
White's position.}) 17. a5 Ng4 {A move just to provoke some reaction from
White. On its own, this move is not threatening anything. But maybe we can
raise the threat of f5 if the queen moves somewhere.} (17... Bd7 {Was another
way to continue.}) 18. Qb1 Bd7 19. f3 (19. h3 {Could have been a more
interesting choice, because now taking on g3 is bad as it opens up the 'f'
file.} Ngf6 {But now Black can open up the king side position using advanced
h3-pawn.} (19... Nxg3 20. fxg3 $16) 20. Bh2 g4 $40) 19... Nxg3 20. hxg3 Nf6 21.
Kf2 h5 {Just like Short, I start my king side play. Black is definitely
enjoying the more pleasant position.} 22. Rh1 Rh8 (22... g4 {Would have been a
natural way to continue. I think White is under quite a lot of pressure in
this position.}) 23. Bf5 Rag8 24. Rh2 g4 25. Reh1 Rg5 26. Bxd7 Qxd7 27. Rh4
Rhg8 (27... gxf3 28. gxf3 Rhg8 {Would have given Black a strong attack.}) 28.
f4 {Now White closes off the king side and is able to reach a safe position.}
exf4 29. exf4 R5g6 30. Re1 Re8 31. Rxe8 Qxe8 32. Qf5 Qd7 {Here, before making
the move, he offered a draw which I accepted! This position is equal, though.
What I would like to take out of this is that my opponent - an experienced IM
- had been playing the Leningrad system for years. I, on the other hand,
prepared against it for a few hours and was able to hold him to a relatively
easy draw! It just shows that Black really is fine in this position.} 1/2-1/2

