{This game might not help us much from the standpoint of the opening theory,
but it is one of classics in this 4.Bg5 Leningrad system. It would be a good
idea to know this classical game! The way in which Spassky saves this game is
a sheer tribute to his talent, calculating ability and creativity.} 1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 {Though this opening is not very popular, Spassky
played 29 games with it and won 17, drew 11 and lost just one - against the
great Mikhail Tal.} h6 5. Bh4 c5 6. d5 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 e5 8. Qc2 d6 9. e3 Qe7 10.
Nf3 Nbd7 (10... Kd8 {Our recommendation is to go to c7 with the king.}) 11. Nd2
e4 $1 {Here Kasparov remarks in his book "My Great Predecessors": Black's
solid bulwarks in the centre deprive the position of the dynamism which the
White bishops so need and restrict any possible activity by White to
diversions on the 'h' and 'b' files. Nowadays the soundness of Black's set up
is known even to young players.} 12. O-O-O O-O $5 {With this interesting move,
the battle flares up.} (12... g5 13. Bg3 Nf8 {With the idea of Ng6 would have
been more normal.}) 13. g4 $1 g5 $1 {Black has a strong centre and hence must
not fear the play on the flank, even if his king is located on that side of
the board.} 14. Bg3 Ne5 15. h3 (15. Nxe4 $2 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Bxg4 {With Bf3
coming up.}) 15... Ng6 {Black has stopped White's activity with h4, as then
the g4 pawn would hang.} 16. Be2 Re8 17. Rdg1 Bd7 18. h4 Rab8 {Kholmov felt
that a6 was better here.} (18... Bxg4 $2 19. Bxg4 Nxg4 20. hxg5 hxg5 21. Bxd6
$16) 19. hxg5 hxg5 20. Rh5 $1 Nxh5 21. gxh5 Nf8 {We might think - why had
White given up the exchange? Is it because he wanted to attack on the king
side? Well, it seems highly improbable with the strong pawn on e4. Spassky
shows why he did what he did.} 22. Nxe4 $3 Qxe4 23. Qxe4 Rxe4 24. Bxd6 {
Winning the second pawn for the rook.} Rbe8 (24... Rc8 25. Rxg5+ {Third pawn.}
Kh8 (25... Kh7 26. Bd3) 26. Be5+ Rxe5 27. Rxe5 Re8 28. Rxe8 Bxe8 29. e4 Nd7 30.
f4 f6 {But it is not possible for Black to win this position.}) 25. Rxg5+ {
Winning the third pawn.} Kh8 26. Bxc5 {And the fourth! White now has four
pawns for the rook and two strong bishops. What imaginative play by the former
world champion!} f6 27. Rg3 b6 28. Bd4 Nh7 29. Kd2 Rg8 30. Rg6 $1 {White does
not mind exchanging pieces.} Be8 31. Bd3 (31. Bxf6+ Nxf6 32. Rxf6 Kg7 $13) (31.
Rxg8+ Kxg8 32. f4 $14 {Gives White quite a pleasant position.}) 31... Bxg6 32.
hxg6 Rxd4 33. cxd4 (33. exd4 {It's funny, but maybe this was stronger.} Nf8 34.
c5 bxc5 35. dxc5 Nd7 36. c6 Nb6 37. c4 $1 $18 {Unlike in the game, we would
have this 'c' pawn coming down the board pushing the knight away from b6. Of
course, while taking on d4 it's difficult to see so far ahead.}) 33... Nf8 34.
c5 bxc5 35. dxc5 Nd7 36. c6 Nb6 {Now the knight is pretty solid on b6 and a
draw should be the logical outcome of the game.} 37. e4 Kg7 38. Ba6 Kxg6 39. a4
Kf7 40. a5 Na8 $1 (40... Nc8 $6 41. f4) 41. Bc4 Rd8 {A draw was agreed here.
Some analysis can show that Black cannot break White's pawns and White cannot
advance them. Hence the game is a draw! Wonderful, imaginative game by the
great Spassky!} 1/2-1/2

